Feature Creation¶

In [724]:
# Avg price per sqft_living
data["price_per_sqft"] = round(data["price"]/data["sqft_living"], 0)

# Bedroom to bathroom ratio
data["bed_bath"] = round(data["bathrooms"]/data["bedrooms"], 1)
data.fillna(0, inplace = True)
data["bed_bath"] = data["bed_bath"].replace([np.inf, -np.inf], 0)

# Datetime
# From date column create three columns: year, month and day
data["year"] = data["date"].apply(lambda x: x[:4])
data["month"] = data["date"].apply(lambda x: x[4:6])
data["day"] = data["date"].apply(lambda x: x[6:8])
data.drop(["date"], axis = 1, inplace = True)
data["datetime"] = pd.to_datetime(data[["year", "month",  "day"]])


# Years since last renovation
# Years since built - the age of the house
now = datetime.datetime.now()
data["age"] = data["yr_built"].apply(lambda x: (now.year - x))

# Function for apply
def years_since_renovation(row):
    if row["yr_renovated"] == 0:
        return row["age"]
    else:
        return (now.year - row["yr_renovated"])
# Extract the years since renovation
data["yr_renovated"] = data.apply(lambda row: years_since_renovation(row), axis = 1)

# The lot size is not a good indicator of the house price
# It is likely that the bigger the lot the futher away the property is from the centre, or expesive areas
# Therefore, the bigger lot does not necesseraly mean a more expensive property

Comments¶

The lot size is likely to be useful feature, because the bigger lot sizes are most often found outside the expensive zipcodes, therefore implies a cheaper price per sqft

Correlation Analysis¶

In [726]:
plt.figure(figsize = (12, 9))
sns.heatmap(data[["price", "bedrooms", \
                  "bathrooms", "sqft_living", "sqft_lot", "view", "grade", "sqft_above", "bed_bath", "sqft_living15", "sqft_lot15", "sqft_basement", \
                  "yr_renovated", "floors", "price_per_sqft", "condition"]].corr(), annot=True)
plt.show()

Comments¶

1) Top 3 correlated features with price: 

 - sqft_living (0.7) 
 - grade (0.67) 
 - sqft_above (0.61)

these features are highly correlated among themselves, which means after adding one of them to the model,
adding the subsequent features may bring limited impact onto the accuracy of the model

2) sqft_living15 less correlated than sqft_living, therefore use sqft_living
3) sqft_lot not highly correlated with price (as expected)
4) Slight negative correlation between price and year since last renovation (as expected)
5) Other useful features: 

- bathrooms (0.53) 
- which is higher than bedrooms (0.31)
- view (0.4)

Price per sqft
There is a small positive correlation between price per sqft and: 

 - view (0.22)
 - years since last renovation (0.25)

This means the price includes a premium for property with the good view and recent renovation

price_by_zip = data.groupby("zipcode").agg({"price_per_sqft": \
                                            [np.mean, np.std, ]}).sort_values(by = ("price_per_sqft", "std"),\
                                                                            ascending = False)[:20].sort_values(by = \
                                                                                                                ("price_per_sqft","mean"), ascending = False)
var_per_per_zip = price_by_zip.iloc[:, 1] / price_by_zip.iloc[:, 0] 
mean_std_zipcode = data.groupby("zipcode").agg({"price_per_sqft": [np.mean, np.std]})
mean_std_zipcode["perc_var"] = mean_std_zipcode[("price_per_sqft", "std")] / mean_std_zipcode[("price_per_sqft", "mean")]

Identify areas with similar types of properties (Clustering)¶

In [519]:
# data reshape
zipcode_df = data.groupby("zipcode").agg({"price_per_sqft": np.mean,\
                                          "sqft_lot": np.mean, "waterfront": np.sum})
zipcode_df_norm = normalize(zipcode_df, axis = 0)

# Find the best number of clusters
scores = []
for i in range(2, 15):
    km = KMeans(n_clusters=i)
    km.fit(zipcode_df_norm)
    zipcode_df["group"] = km.labels_
    sil_score = silhouette_score(zipcode_df_norm, km.labels_, metric = "euclidean")
    scores.append(sil_score)
plt.figure(figsize = (15, 4))
plt.plot(np.arange(2, 15), scores)
plt.xticks(np.arange(2, 15))
plt.show()
# if we use 3 clusters, it gives the highest Silhouette score

Modelling¶

In [310]:
def Regression_models_analysis(MLA, X, y):
    warnings.filterwarnings("ignore")
    #create table to compare MLA metrics
    MLA_columns = ['MLA Name', 'MLA Parameters','MLA Test MSQE', 'MLA Test R2', 'MLA Test MAX error', 'MLA Time']
    MLA_compare = pd.DataFrame(columns = MLA_columns)

    #create table to compare MLA predictions
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = 0.2, random_state = 0)
    MLA_predict = pd.DataFrame(y_test)

    #index through MLA and save performance to table
    row_index = 0
    for alg in MLA:
        #set name and parameters
        MLA_name = alg.__class__.__name__
        MLA_compare.loc[row_index, 'MLA Name'] = MLA_name
        MLA_compare.loc[row_index, 'MLA Parameters'] = str(alg.get_params())

        #score model with cross validation: http://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.model_selection.cross_validate.html#sklearn.model_selection.cross_validate
        scores = cross_validate(alg, X, y, cv = 5, scoring = ("neg_mean_squared_error", "r2", "max_error"))

        MLA_compare.loc[row_index, 'MLA Time'] = scores["fit_time"].mean()
        MLA_compare.loc[row_index, 'MLA Test MSQE'] = format(int(scores["test_neg_mean_squared_error"].mean()), ",d")
        MLA_compare.loc[row_index, 'MLA Test R2'] = scores["test_r2"].mean()   
        MLA_compare.loc[row_index, 'MLA Test MAX error'] =   format(int(scores["test_max_error"].max()), ",d")

        #save MLA predictions
        alg.fit(X_train, y_train)
        MLA_predict[MLA_name] = alg.predict(X_test)
        row_index += 1


    #print and sort table: https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/generated/pandas.DataFrame.sort_values.html
    MLA_compare.sort_values(by = ['MLA Test R2'], ascending = False, inplace = True)
    #MLA_predict
    return MLA_compare, MLA_predict

def show_errors(m1_result, col):
    m1_analysis = m1_result[["price", col]]
    m1_analysis["diff"] = m1_analysis[col] - m1_analysis["price"]
    plt.figure(figsize = (10, 8))
    plt.scatter(m1_analysis["price"], m1_analysis["diff"], s= 10)
    plt.xlabel("Price")
    plt.ylabel("Diff = prediction - price")
    plt.xticks(np.linspace(0, 5000000, 6, dtype = np.int), [format(x, ",d") for x in np.linspace(0, 5000000, 6, dtype = np.int)])
    plt.yticks(np.linspace(-1500000, 2000000, 8, dtype = np.int), [format(x, ",d") for x in np.linspace(-1500000, 2000000, 8, dtype = np.int)])

# DATA PREPARATION
# Choose the columns
sales = data[["sqft_living", "grade", "zipcode", "price", "datetime"]]

# Remove duplicates, keep only last one
sales = sales.sort_values(by = "datetime", ascending=False)
sales.drop_duplicates(subset = ["sqft_living", "grade", "zipcode"], \
                      keep='first', inplace=True)

# check duplicates
# np.unique(sales.index, return_counts=True)[0][np.unique(sales.index, return_counts=True)[1]>1]

# Convert non numeric columns to numeric -> Dummy encoder
# Zipcode -> it is non ordinary variable therefore we use pd.get_dummies to encode this variable
# Since there any many variables, the quality of regression is likely to decline from using zipcode as it is
sales = pd.merge(sales, pd.get_dummies(sales["zipcode"]), left_index = True, right_index = True).drop(["zipcode"], axis = 1)

sales.drop(["datetime"], axis = 1, inplace= True)

# DATA PREPARATION
# Choose the columns
sales = data[["sqft_living", "grade", "zipcode", "age", "sqft_lot15", "waterfront", "sqft_above", "bathrooms", "price",  "datetime"]]

# Remove duplicates, keep only last one
sales = sales.sort_values(by = "datetime", ascending=False)
sales.drop_duplicates(subset = ["sqft_living", "grade", "zipcode", "age", "sqft_lot15", "waterfront", "sqft_above", "bathrooms"], \
                      keep='first', inplace=True)

# check duplicates
# np.unique(sales.index, return_counts=True)[0][np.unique(sales.index, return_counts=True)[1]>1]

# Convert non numeric columns to numeric -> Dummy encoder
# Zipcode -> it is non ordinary variable therefore we use pd.get_dummies to encode this variable
# Since there any many variables, the quality of regression is likely to decline from using zipcode as it is
sales = pd.merge(sales, pd.get_dummies(sales["zipcode"]), left_index = True, right_index = True).drop(["zipcode"], axis = 1)

# lot_size is the ordinary variable, therefore can encode using 
# lot_size_mapping = {"small" : 0, "medium": 1, "large": 2}
# sales["lot_size_num"] = sales["lot_size"].apply(lambda x: lot_size_mapping[x])

sales.drop(["datetime"], axis = 1, inplace= True)

# Analyse neighbour model result
KNN_result = m2_result[["price", "RandomForestRegressor"]]
KNN_result["diff"] = KNN_result["RandomForestRegressor"] - KNN_result["price"] 
KNN_result["diff_perc"] = round(KNN_result["diff"] / KNN_result["price"], 2)
KNN_data = pd.merge(data.drop("price", axis = 1), KNN_result, left_index = True, right_index = True, how = "right")
KNN_data["geometry"] = KNN_data.apply(lambda x: Point(x["long"], x["lat"]), axis = 1)
sale_points_gdf = gpd.GeoDataFrame(KNN_data[["zipcode", "diff", "diff_perc", "geometry"]],
                         crs={'init' :'epsg:4326'})

count_diff = KNN_data[abs(KNN_data["diff_perc"]) > 0.20].groupby("zipcode").count()["diff"].reset_index().rename(columns = {"diff" : "count_diff_0.2"})
KNN_data = pd.merge(KNN_data, count_diff, left_on = "zipcode", right_on = "zipcode", how = "left")

pred_analysis_gdf = pd.merge(gdf, KNN_data.groupby("zipcode").agg({"diff": np.mean, "diff_perc": np.mean, "count_diff_0.2": np.mean}), \
                             left_index =True, right_index = True )
pred_analysis_gdf["abs_diff"] = [abs(x) for x in pred_analysis_gdf["diff"]]
pred_analysis_gdf["abs_diff_perc"] = [abs(x) for x in pred_analysis_gdf["diff_perc"]]

zipcodes_with_highest_diff = KNN_data[abs(KNN_data["diff_perc"]) > 1].zipcode.tolist()

Comments¶

By moving from a 3 feature model to 8 feature model:
1) R2 have increased from around 0.76 to 0.82
2) Maximum error has decreased substantially from 2m to 1.2m 3) Mean squared error (MSQ) has also declined substantially 4) Top 2 models are Random Forest and KNN


Map check¶

Visualize each zipcode area where the property prices have been underestamted by more than 20%
And plot the property locations with price % difference less than 20% (more or less accurate estimate) in black
And plot the property locations with price % difference more than 20% (inaccurate estimate) in red
To estimate if there are specific location hubs where properties are more luxurious/ expensive and that model does not pick up


In [767]:
for i in range(len(zipcodes_with_highest_diff)):
    base = pred_analysis_gdf[pred_analysis_gdf.index == zipcodes_with_highest_diff[i]].plot(color = "grey", figsize=(15, 8), legend = True)
    temp_point = sale_points_gdf[sale_points_gdf["zipcode"] == zipcodes_with_highest_diff[i]]
    temp_point = temp_point.to_crs(zip_codes.crs)
    temp_point[abs(temp_point["diff_perc"]) < 0.2].plot(ax=base, marker = "o", color = "black", markersize=5)
    temp_point[abs(temp_point["diff_perc"]) > 0.2].plot(ax=base, marker = "o", color = "red", markersize=10)

    plt.xticks([])
    plt.yticks([])
    plt.title(zipcodes_with_highest_diff[0], fontsize = 14)
    plt.show()

Comments¶

Many zipcode areas show the correctly estimated house prices are in close proximity to incorrectly estimated house prices
However, in some cases, there are areas with red dots (inaccurately estimated house prices) that are away from other properties
Since we can see that price per sqft depends on the location/ street/ area,
It could be useful to divide the spacial locations into a finer grids, and use these grids as features

Future ideas¶

1) Divide the spatial area into grids and treat each grid as a feature to achieve a finer spatial separation between properties
